<DocsLayout title="Browser Sessions" description="Configure browser sidecars for authenticated Reddit, Twitter, and LinkedIn crawling.">
  <h1>Browser Sessions</h1>

  <p style="margin-top: 16px;">
    LeadEcho supports authenticated crawling of Reddit, Twitter, and LinkedIn by
    maintaining real browser sessions via sidecars. This unlocks significantly more content
    than unauthenticated scraping and avoids rate-limiting.
  </p>

  <h2>Sidecar Options</h2>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Sidecar</th>
        <th>Technology</th>
        <th>Platforms</th>
        <th>Docker Profile</th>
        <th>Port</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Pinchtab</strong></td>
        <td>Persistent Chrome + anti-bot fingerprint spoofing</td>
        <td>Reddit, Twitter, LinkedIn</td>
        <td><code>browser</code></td>
        <td>9867</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Camoufox</strong></td>
        <td>Stealth Firefox + human-mimicry fingerprinting</td>
        <td>LinkedIn (Pro tier)</td>
        <td><code>browser-pro</code></td>
        <td>9868</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Scrapling</strong></td>
        <td>Adaptive CSS-based extraction</td>
        <td>Fallback general crawling</td>
        <td><code>browser-scrapling</code></td>
        <td>9869</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Pinchtab Setup</h2>

  <p>Pinchtab is the primary sidecar for authenticated social crawling.</p>

  <pre><code># Start Pinchtab alongside the main stack
docker compose --profile browser up -d

# Required environment variables:
PINCHTAB_TOKEN=your-token
PINCHTAB_URL=http://localhost:9867  # default</code></pre>

  <h2>Camoufox Pro Setup</h2>

  <p>
    Camoufox provides stealth Firefox-based browsing with advanced fingerprint spoofing.
    It activates automatically when <code>CAMOUFOX_URL</code> is set in the environment.
  </p>

  <pre><code># Start with Camoufox Pro sidecar
CAMOUFOX_URL=http://localhost:9868 docker compose --profile browser-pro up -d</code></pre>

  <h2>Scrapling Fallback</h2>

  <p>
    Scrapling uses adaptive CSS selectors that self-heal when site layouts change.
    It serves as a fallback when Pinchtab or Camoufox are unavailable.
  </p>

  <pre><code>docker compose --profile browser-scrapling up -d

# Environment:
SCRAPLING_URL=http://localhost:9869
SCRAPLING_TOKEN=your-token</code></pre>

  <h2>Session Cookie Configuration</h2>

  <p>
    Once a sidecar is running, you need to provide your account session cookies so the browser
    can authenticate. Navigate to <strong>Dashboard → Browser Sessions</strong> and paste cookies
    for each platform.
  </p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Platform</th>
        <th>Cookie Name</th>
        <th>Where to Find It</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Reddit</td>
        <td><code>reddit_session</code></td>
        <td>DevTools → Application → Cookies → reddit.com</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Twitter / X</td>
        <td><code>auth_token</code></td>
        <td>DevTools → Application → Cookies → x.com</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>LinkedIn</td>
        <td><code>li_at</code></td>
        <td>DevTools → Application → Cookies → linkedin.com</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <blockquote>
    <p>
      <strong>Security:</strong> Session cookies are encrypted with AES-256 using your
      <code>ENCRYPTION_KEY</code> before being stored in the <code>platform_accounts</code> table.
      They are never logged or exposed in API responses.
    </p>
  </blockquote>

  <h3>Session Cookie API</h3>

  <pre><code>PUT /api/v1/settings/sessions/&#123;platform&#125;
Authorization: Bearer &lt;jwt&gt;
Content-Type: application/json

&#123;
  "cookies": "reddit_session=abc123...",
  "username": "myredditusername"
&#125;

# Test a session
POST /api/v1/settings/sessions/&#123;platform&#125;/test
Authorization: Bearer &lt;jwt&gt;</code></pre>

  <h3>Test Response</h3>

  <pre><code>&#123;
  "ok": true,
  "username": "myredditusername",
  "platform": "reddit",
  "tested_at": "2025-03-01T10:00:00Z"
&#125;</code></pre>

